            Output
print()
    outputs whatever is inside the ()

print(value, ..., sep='', end='/n', file=sys.stdout, flush=False)
    value -> will output a comma separated list of data
    sep='' -> default separator for the comma separated list of data
    end='/n' -> default ending for the output. /n will start on new line
    flie=sys.stdout -> where the output will be displayed to. shell or a file


             Comments
Can be single line or multiple lines
Single line: good for short, quick comments
    Basic format -> #information
Multiple: describing in detail or blocking out code
    Basic format ->  '''
                        information
                     '''


            Using Variables
Variables are the heart of every good programming language
Python interprets and declares variables when set a value to them
    a = 0   b = 2
    print(a + b) -> 2

Python will figure out the type of variable
    a = "0" b = "2"
    print(a + b) -> 02

Python allows you to cast variables to other data types
    a = "0"  b = 2
    print(int(a) + b) -> 2

int(variable) - casts variable to integer
str(variable) - casts variable to string
float(variable) - casts variable to float (number with decimal)

Variable names can only contain the following characters:
    lowercase letters (a through z)
    uppercase letts (A through Z)
    digits (0 through 9)
    underscore (_)


            Basic Input
Input
    Basic format -> input()
        calling this will allow you to input a string type of data
        can set equal to a variable too
    Advanced format -> input("Prompt the user: ")
        adds a prompt message to the input 


            Basic Arithmetic Operations
Addition (1 + 2) Subtraction (1 - 2) Multiplication (1 * 2) Division (1 / 2)


            Advanced Operators
Modulus (3 % 4) Powers (3 ** 4) Floor Division (3 // 4) Assignment Operator (3 += 4)